The '''Berkeley Geochronology Center''' ('''BGC''') is a [[501(c)|non-profit]] [[geochronology]] [[research institute]] in [[Berkeley, California]]. It was originally a research group in the laboratory of [[University of California Berkeley]] [[geophysics|geophysicist]] and [[geochronology|geochronologist]] [[Garniss Curtis]], now [[Emeritus|professor emeritus]].<ref name="SwisherEtAl2001">{{cite book|last=Swisher|first=Carl C.|coauthors=Garniss H. Curtis, and Roger Lewin|title=Java Man: How Two Geologists Changed Our Understanding of Human Evolution|pages=107–108|date=2001|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn-13=9780226787343}}</ref>  The group is now an independent scientific research institute directed by the  geologist and geochronologist [[Paul Renne]], adjunct professor of Earth & Planetary Sciences at Berkeley.

In 1985, Curtis, set to retire in 1989, moved the group from his lab at the University to the basement of the independent [[Donald Johanson|Institute for Human Origins]] (IHO), at the suggestion of [[United States of America|American]] [[anthropology|anthropologist]] [[Francis Clark Howell|F. Clark Howell]]. <ref name="SwisherEtAl2001" />  The geochronologists worked separately from the IHO, although IHO contained their bureaucratic infrastructure, until 1989 when they became officially known as the Institute for Human Origins Geochronology Center.<ref name="SwisherEtAl2001" />   In 1994 the group officially split from the IHO based on different viewpoints of their respective missions.<ref name="KalbKalb2000">{{cite book|last=Kalb|first=Jon|title= Adventures in the Bone Trade: The Race to Discover Our Ancestors in Ethiopia's Afar Depression|pages=298–299|date=2000|publisher= Springer-Verlag New York, LLC|isbn-13=9780387987422}}</ref><ref name="SwisherEtAl2001" />  

The Institute specializes in fundamental questions of the age of the earth, using state-of-the-art instrumentation to find the age of rocks that will answer questions about [[geology]] and [[geobiology]] in [[History of the Earth|earth history]].  The institute is capable of performing gas extraction, and thermal ionization [[mass spectrometry]] analysis on rocks up to billions of years old using the techniques of [[argon–argon dating]] and [[uranium-lead dating]].  BGC also performs [[paleomagnetism|paleomagnetic]] analysis to  establish correlating or independent ages from the fossilized magnetic fields.  The staff includes research scientists specializing in various geological periods and areas, in addition to postdoctoral scholars and graduate students.  Scientists at BGC have also been active in dating extraterrestrial materials such as meteorites.<ref name="Whitehouse">{{cite web|last= Whitehouse|first=David|title='Four-billion-year chill' on Mars|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/4703055.stm|date=2005-07-21|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=2009-02-07}}</ref>

==Split from Institute for Human Origins==
Both Curtis and IHO founder, [[Donald Johanson]], were known to have egos that might "clash", but Howell thought that bringing the two research groups together could benefit both.<ref name="SwisherEtAl2001" />  The IHO's mission included publicizing the anthropology of ancient human ancestors to the general public, and the geochronology scientists felt the anthropologists emphasized this at the expense of more basic science, while the paleoanthropologist felt the geochronologists were devoting too much research time and funding to general geology questions not related to the institute's primary mission.<ref name="SwisherEtAl2001" />  The anthropologists had more public recognition in the press, while the geochronologists were obtaining more scientific grant moneys and publishing more scientific papers.<ref name="SwisherEtAl2001" />  The split was acrimonious and garnered negative publicity for some of those involved from their peers in professional organizations, particularly as [[Gordon Getty]], the single largest donor, and a board member of IHO, withdrew funding to the parent institute (IHO), while providing start-up moneys to the geochronology group. <ref name="SwisherEtAl2001" /><ref name="KalbKalb2000" />    

