Distonic ions are chemical species that contain both a radical and an ionic site on different atoms of the same molecule.<ref>{{GoldBookRef|title=distonic radical cation|file=D01809}}</ref><ref name=Stirk1992>{{Cite journal | last = Stirk | first =  Krista M. | year = 1992 | title = Ion-molecule reactions of distonic radical cations | journal = Chemical Reviews | volume = 92 | pages = 1649 | doi = 10.1021/cr00015a008}}</ref> They were first discovered in the gas phase by Michael L. Gross.<ref name=Holman1986>{{Cite journal | last = Holman | first =  R. | year = 1986 | title = Mass spectrometry for investigations of gas-phase radical cation chemistry the two step cycloaddition of the benzene radical cation and 1,3-butadiene | journal = Tetrahedron | volume = 42 | pages = 6235 | doi = 10.1016/S0040-4020(01)88085-6}}</ref> In recent years there has been a tremendous effort to identify new distonic species, characterize their reactivity, and measure their stability.<ref name="pmid">{{cite journal |author=Tomazela DM, Sabino AA, Sparrapan R, Gozzo FC, Eberlin MN |title=Distonoid ions |journal=J. Am. Soc. Mass Spectrom. |volume=17 |issue=7 |pages=1014–22 |year=2006 |month=July|doi=10.1016/j.jasms.2006.03.008 |url=http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S1044-0305(06)00271-6}}</ref><ref name="pmid17286357">{{cite journal |author=Ibrahim Y, Mabrouki R, Meot-Ner M, El-Shall MS |title=Hydrogen bonding interactions of pyridine*+ with water: stepwise solvation of distonic cations |journal=J Phys Chem A |volume=111 |issue=6 |pages=1006–14 |year=2007 |month=February |pmid=17286357 |doi=10.1021/jp067390h}}</ref><ref name="pmid17200931">{{cite journal |author=Bouchoux G, Berruyer F, Hiberty PC, Wu W |title=Classical and distonic radical cations: a valence bond approach |journal=Chemistry |volume=13 |issue=10 |pages=2912–9 |year=2007 |pmid=17200931 |doi=10.1002/chem.200600985 |url=}}</ref>

