||
}}
=Ruy Lopez, Riga Variation, Main Line=

After all the active play, the dust is about to settle. Each side has a minor piece still in jeopardy. Black's best move here is to simply take the white knight, with [[/13...Kxd8|13...Kxd8]]. White will follow up by taking black's h2 bishop.

{{ChessMid}}
==References==
{{reflist}}
{{wikipedia|Ruy Lopez}}

{{Chess Opening Theory/Footer}}

{{Chess Opening Theory/Position|=
|Ruy Lopez:Riga Variation|
   |rd|  |bd|kd|  |  |  |rd|=
   |  |pd|pd|  |  |pd|pd|pd|=
   |pd|  |  |  |  |  |  |  |=
   |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |=
   |bl|  |  |  |pd|  |  |  |=
   |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |=
   |pl|pl|pl|  |  |pl|pl|bd|=
   |rl|nl|bl|  |  |  |  |kl|=
||
}}
=Ruy Lopez, Riga Variation, Main Line=

Black takes the hanging knight. White should reciprocate by moving [[/14. Kxh2|14. Kxh2]]. All other moves are inferior, as anything but Kxh2 or g3 will allow the bishop to get away. Moving g3 traps the bishop, but allows it to take another pawn before it dies.

{{ChessMid}}
==References==
{{reflist}}
{{wikipedia|Ruy Lopez}}

{{Chess Opening Theory/Footer}}

{{Chess Opening Theory/Position|=
|Ruy Lopez:Riga Variation|
   |rd|  |bd|kd|  |  |  |rd|=
   |  |pd|pd|  |  |pd|pd|pd|=
   |pd|  |  |  |  |  |  |  |=
   |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |=
   |bl|  |  |  |pd|  |  |  |=
   |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |  |=
   |pl|pl|pl|  |  |pl|pl|kl|=
   |rl|nl|bl|  |  |  |  |  |=
||
}}
=Ruy Lopez, Riga Variation, Main Line=

White has taken the hanging bishop, and material balance has been restored. After the dust settles, white has a knight and bishop (and the bishop pair) for a rook and two pawns. 

Now, black must see to the protection of the weak f pawn and counter white's active light squared bishop. The move here is [[/14...Be6|14...Be6]]. This contains white's bishop, giving it nowhere to go without being taken. If white plays poorly, black may be able to trap the bishop as well. Other moves allow white's bishop to occupy the a2-g8 diagonal first.

{{ChessMid}}
